<html>
<title> How Freeing America's Farmers Would Mean A $135 Billion Boost -- Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">

<center>

<h3> HOW FREEING AMERICA'S FARMERS WOULD MEAN A $135 BILLION BOOST </h3>

John E. Frydenlund<br> 
Director, Agricultural Policy Project<br>
and<br>
<a href="/heritage/staff/winston.htm">David H. Winston</a><br>
Senior Fellow in Statistical Policy Analysis<p>

<a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a><br>
Issue Bulletin No. 214<br>
September 19, 1995<br>
<hr width=50%></center>

<p>
<b>INTRODUCTION</b>
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;

	The 104th Congress has a rare opportunity to reform American agricultural policy and provide a huge boost to the U.S. economy. The current system of centrally planned commodity support programs, export subsidies, supply controls, acreage allotments, production quotas, and restrictions on trade imports holds back American farmers. This makes it impossible for them to benefit from the growing world market and denies farming-related industries the economic boost of higher farm production.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;Freeing the U.S. farm economy -- farmers and related businesses -- to take full advantage of the growing global market would mean huge economic benefits for Americans. An analysis by Heritage Senior Fellow David Winston and Research Analysts Rea Hederman and Christine L. Olson indicates that such reform would generate as much as $135 billion in new economic activity over ten years.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	In <I>Freeing America's Farmers:  The Heritage Plan for Rural Prosperity</I>, The Heritage Foundation has proposed that Congress immediately end all supply control programs.<sup>1</sup> The Conservation Reserve Program (CRP), which is more a supply control than conservation program, harms the rural economy more than all other supply control programs combined because it keeps about 36 million acres out of production. The Heritage plan would reform the CRP immediately by neither renewing expiring contracts nor entering into any new ones. Farmers with existing contracts would be given the option to withdraw from the program before their contract expiration date. In return, they would receive 33 percent of the payment to which they otherwise would have been entitled for the duration of their contract.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	Two legislative proposals before Congress:  the Farm Freedom Act (H.R. 2010), sponsored by Representatives Richard Zimmer (R-NJ) and Charles Schumer (D-NY), and the Freedom to Farm Act (H.R. 2195), sponsored by House Agriculture Committee Chairman Pat Roberts (R-KS), would end the use of annual supply controls for the wheat, feed grain, cotton, and rice programs. However, neither addresses the fundamental CRP problem. Only proposals that remove the federal government from the business of managing supply and demand can increase farm income from the marketplace while stimulating overall economic growth.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	If farmers were free of the controls that now restrict output, they would enjoy a surge in new income even when modest declines in prices are taken into account. The comprehensive model of the agriculture economy developed by The Heritage Foundation indicates that additional net farm income from the marketplace in 1996 would exceed $2 billion. By the year 2001, it would be nearly $4 billion, and between 1996 and 2001, it would exceed $18 billion. The state-by-state impact on farm income of the Heritage Foundation's agriculture reform proposal can be found in <I>Freeing America's Farmers</I>.
<p><b>

HOW INCREASED FARM INCOME WILL PRODUCE AN ECONOMIC BOOM FOR STATES</b>
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	Although some states would not immediately make dramatic farm income gains or would take longer to become net farm income winners, farmers in most states would gain significantly under the Heritage plan.<sup>2</sup> But an increase in farm production also has an economic impact on farm-related business. Freeing U.S. farmers would bring millions of previously idle acres back into productive use. This would require increased use of agricultural inputs, such as seed, fertilizer, and equipment, in addition to expansion of the food processing industry and greater demand for packaging, transportation, and shipping.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	The appendix presents state-level data for 1996-2005 to show the value of the additional economic activity that would be generated by changes in farm income under the Heritage agriculture reform proposal. In this ten-year period, the overall economy would expand by $134.9 billion, with every state sharing in the economic expansion. Even some states that are not major agricultural producers would enjoy a boost because they supply farmers elsewhere or handle farm products. In fact, the national economy would grow by $10.9 billion in just the first year. And states benefit because they have business activity related to the farm economy.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	Example:  Kansas and Texas each would enjoy a $1 billion boost to the economy in the first year, and Iowa would benefit by almost $800 million. States with significant agricultural production, such as Kansas (a large wheat producer), Iowa (a leading corn producer), or Texas (a large state producing many crops), reap the greatest economic benefits because most of the increased economic activity would remain in the state in which the additional farm income is generated.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	Example:  Even non-agriculture states reap sizable economic benefits. Because the Heritage analysis assumes that as much as 75 percent of the new production would go to the export market, a number of states with significant export facilities but minimal agricultural production would receive large economic benefits. For instance, although a state like Rhode Island does not produce a great quantity of agricultural product, its economy would benefit from increased shipping and transportation activities, especially those related to exports. In fact, any state with significant export activities or port facilities, such as Louisiana and a number of other coastal and Great Lakes states, would derive more in benefits than they have contributed through increased agricultural production.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	Also, a major share of the increased agricultural production would mean new business for firms engaged in processing, converting raw agricultural commodities into value-added products for both export and domestic use, and livestock production. Therefore, any state with a significant livestock industry or food processing facilities also would gain more than it generates simply through increased agricultural production. 

<p>
<b>CONCLUSION</b>
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	In the next few weeks, Congress will consider the 1995 farm bill, probably as a part of budget reconciliation. Congress must take advantage of this compelling opportunity to effect fundamental reforms in U.S. agricultural policy. If the 1995 farm bill eliminates supply controls such as acreage reduction programs, ends the government's role in manipulating supply and demand through subsidies, and phases out the CRP, not only will farm income increase significantly, but the national economy will expand by over $135 billion over the next ten years. 
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	 Some Members of Congress have advocated proposals that would do nothing more than protect the status quo and thus would fail to capture any of these potential gains. On the other hand, two proposals, H.R. 2010 and H.R. 2195, do eliminate some of the supply control programs, which would benefit farmers and related businesses. However, unless Congress enacts complete reform, including termination of the CRP, the U.S. economy will be denied the growth that can be achieved only with an end to central planning in agriculture. 

<p>
<b>APPENDIX:  THE HERITAGE FOUNDATION MODEL</b><p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
The Heritage Foundation Farm Income Projection Model, described in detail in <I>Freeing America's Farmers</I>, projects what would happen to future farm income (1996-2005) should just over three-quarters of all idled land come back into production, based on a historical analysis of the farm sector from 1990-1993. In our model we assumed that overall, about 80 percent of government-idled land would come back into production. These additional acres would yield only 95 percent as much as land currently being farmed, and costs of production would be 5 percent higher. For all cropland in our analysis, yields would increase 0.5 percent each through 2005 due to productivity gains. Finally, we assumed that because of growing overseas demand, the increase in supply would have a minimal impact on prices. The greatest effect would be in 1996, when prices would drop 4 percent. By 2005 this loss would be more than recouped.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	In keeping with estimates of the gain in farm income contained in <I>Freeing America's Farmers</I>, the Heritage Foundation's more comprehensive estimates of increased economic activity are conservative in their assumptions. In the model to estimate farm income gains, we assumed that future productivity gains would be only one half of one percent annually and estimated relatively higher costs of production for new acreage relative to existing acreage. Thus, the model significantly understated potential income gains, and our conclusions about changes in farm income presented the worst case scenario, suggesting that some states would take much longer to become net farm income winners.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	Some states would take longer because the model assumed that farmers would continue to grow whatever crop they previously produced or currently were producing and that production on new acreage would simply reflect their historical growing patterns, even when this would cause a loss of income. However, if allowed to produce for the marketplace rather than for the government, farmers would not use their available acreage to produce any crop that resulted in a negative income. If there is no alternative crop available to generate a net profit from production on the new acreage, the farmer's rational decision would be to leave that land idle rather than produce a crop at a loss. Therefore, our model showed income losses for farmers when, at worst, there would have been no gain.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	By comparison, a study by Abel, Daft and Early estimated an expansion of $28.9 billion dollars for one year, based on ending supply controls.<sup>3</sup> However, their estimate also assumed that there was no reduction in deficiency payments, which then were credited with contributing to the overall economy.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	In estimating the additional economic activity generated by increases in farm income, we assumed that most, though not all, of the new product will be sold overseas to meet the growing demand for food in Africa and the Pacific Rim. While it is true that increased production could trigger faster development of new consumer products and new uses for the domestic market as well as for the international market, we estimate only the increase in economic activity that would be derived from increases in exports.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
	The Heritage analysis is based on the gross business multiplier of all agricultural exports developed by Gerald Schluter and William Edmondson of the U.S. Department of Agriculture's Economic Research Service. Their multiplier factor is based on a recognition that "in a highly interrelated economy like that of the United States, many more people benefit from agricultural exports than just farmers and exporters and their employees."  Schluter and Edmondson specifically point to firms that provide materials and services used by farmers and others to provide the export goods as beneficiaries of increased economic activity that leads to business growth, in addition to businesses which sell consumer goods and find that their customers spend more income when trade expands.<sup>4</sup>
<p><b>ENDNOTES</b><ul><p><li>

    John E. Frydenlund, <I>Freeing America's Farmers:  The Heritage Plan for Rural Prosperity</I> (Washington, D.C.:  The Heritage Foundation, 1995).
 <p><li>    There were insufficient data for an analysis of Alaska and Hawaii.
  <p><li>  <I>Large-Scale Land Idling Has Retarded Growth of U.S. Agriculture</I>, a study by Abel, Daft and Early, an economic analysis consulting firm in Alexandria, Virginia, on behalf of the <I>U.S. Agriculture 20/20 Project</I> of the National Grain and Feed Foundation, May 1994.
   <p><li> Gerald Schluter and William Edmondson, <I>USDA's Agricultural Trade Multipliers</I>, United States Department of Agriculture, Economic Research Service, Agriculture Information Bulletin No. 697, April 1994.
</ol><p><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER>

</body></html>

 


