<html>
<title>Questions and Answers on "Truth in Testimony" - Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>

<h3>QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS ON "TRUTH IN TESTIMONY" </h3>
<b>A Government Reform Project Study</b>
<p>
By <a href="/heritage/staff/weinstein.html"> Kenneth R. Weinstein</a><br>
Director, Government Reform Project<br>
and August Stofferahn, Research Assistant<sup>1</sup>
<p>
<a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a><br>
F.Y.I.  No. 125<br>
December 16, 1996<br>
<br>

<hr width=50%></center>
<p>
<dd>The House of Representatives is considering a new "Truth in Testimony" rule requiring witnesses that receive federal funds through government contracts to disclose the amount and source of the funds when they testify before congressional committees.<sup>1</sup>  Many of the objections to this rule concern its implementation rather than the principle of disclosure. This paper answers some of the most frequently asked questions about the Truth in Testimony rule and how it would work in practice. 
<p>
<b>Q: What is Truth in Testimony?</b>
<p>
A: Truth in Testimony is an amendment to the Rules of the House of Representatives, introduced by Representative John Doolittle (R-CA), that would require witnesses before congressional committees to disclose the amount of funding they receive from the federal government through grants or contracts.
<p>
<b>
Q: What is the goal of Truth in Testimony? </b>
<p>
A: It aims to give Congress more information about the background of congressional witnesses. By requiring witnesses to disclose their federal grants and contracts, Congress can learn whether a witness may have a vested interest in the subject under a committee's examination. Further, since congressional hearings often are the focus of media reports, this rule would alert the media and the public to any testimony that may be financially self-serving.
<p>
<b>
Q: Is Truth in Testimony a "gag rule"?</b>
<p>
A: No. Truth in Testimony is a sunshine law designed to elicit more information about witnesses appearing before congressional committees. It would not impose restrictions on the testimony of any witness, nor would it restrict the activities pursued by federal grantees.
<p>
<b>
Q: Who supports Truth in Testimony? </b>
<p>
A: The proposal was part of the 1996 Republican platform and is now under consideration in the House of Representatives. In addition to Congressman Doolittle, the idea also has the support of Representative Bob Livingston (Chairman of the House Appropriations Committee), Representative Gerald Solomon (Chairman of the House Rules Committee), Representative Tom DeLay (House Republican Whip), Representative George Radanovich (president of the freshman class during the 104th Congress), and other committee chairmen. The proposed rules change has been endorsed by several outside organizations, such as Americans for Tax Reform, the Christian Coalition, 60 Plus, National Right to Work, and Eagle Forum, among others.
<p>
<b>
Q: How would it work? </b>
<p>
A: Truth in Testimony would amend the House Rules and affect all committees and subcommittees, including authorizing and appropriations committees. The chairman of the committee or subcommittee would notify witnesses in advance of hearings that their written statements must disclose the amount of federal grants or contracts that they receive. If the witness does not make a good faith disclosure, then his or her testimony will not be included in the hearing record.
<p>
<b>
Q: How many witnesses would be affected? </b>
<p>
A: A survey of witnesses testifying in 1995 reveals that at least one of every three "public" (non-federal government) witnesses was a grant recipient. This amounts to roughly 3,000 witnesses each year, only a tiny percentage of whom currently disclose their subsidized status.
<p>
<b>
Q: What exactly would have witnesses have to list? </b>
<p>
A: The proposal would require witnesses, in their written statements, to include the following information about the organizations they represent: "the amount and source (by agency and program) of any federal grants (including subgrants from other organizations or from a state pursuant to a federal block grant) received, and contracts entered into, during the current and previous two fiscal years."
<p>
<b>
Q: Who would be responsible for making sure witnesses comply with Truth in Testimony? </b>
<p>
A: It would be the responsibility of the committee or subcommittee chairman, presumably through the staff, to check for disclosure in written testimony. Any needed clarification could be requested at the hearing or during the process of preparing hearing transcripts for printing. In most cases, witnesses are called to testify either because of their experience with a program, agency, and issue or because Members and staff are familiar with their organizations. Accordingly, the rule would not substantially increase burdens on committee staff.
<p>
<b>
Q: What if a witness fails to disclose the information and no one says anything? </b>
<p>
A: If a witness's statement lacks a grant and contract disclosure, it would be the responsibility of the committee staff to inquire about it. If staff members notice during or after the hearing that a written statement of a grantee or contractor failed to include the required information, then the witness could be contacted for a revision during the time typically allowed for corrections. To avoid any difficulties, witnesses should consult their organization's IRS Form 990, which lists its sources of revenue. Form 990 is a public document that each non-profit organization must file annually; by law, it must be made available for public inspection during regular business hours.
<p>
<b>
Q: What if a witness gives incorrect figures? </b>
<p>
A: The rule requires that witnesses make a "good faith disclosure" of information. If witnesses err inadvertently or through lack of knowledge, they would not be penalized. But if a witness refuses to make disclosure or intentionally provides incorrect information, his statement would be stricken from the record. No other penalties would normally apply since Truth in Testimony is a congressional rule rather than a civil or criminal statute.
<p>
<b>
Q: Does the Truth in Testimony rule include farm subsidies, entitlements, pensions, or benefits? </b>
<p>
A: No. The rule would only deal with federal grants and contracts that produce goods or services for the public at large or specific federal agencies. Such grants and contracts are awarded on a competitive basis by federal agencies. Grant applicants and contract competitors normally file a complicated grant request, and later must complete progress and final reports and financial evaluations of their project. Benefits to individuals, including Social Security, agricultural subsidies, federal pensions, and other entitlement programs would not be covered by Truth in Testimony. Categorical loan programs, such as those for students, small businesses, and disaster victims likewise would not be covered. Individuals automatically receive these entitlements or benefits because they meet certain eligibility requirements as specified by law.
<p>
<b>
Q: Shouldn't Congress already know who receives federal funds? </b>
<p>
A: Grants and contracts typically are issued by executive and independent agencies; Congress appropriates the funds and plays an oversight role. Individual congressional committees, however, do not have the resources to monitor the each of the grants or contracts given out by federal agencies. In a typical year, more than 80 agencies make federal grants totaling $40 billion to over 39,000 different groups.
<p>
<b>Q: Instead of burdening congressional witnesses with a new regulation, why can't this be done on an ad hoc basis? </b>
<p>
A: Without a rule establishing a policy of disclosure, witnesses would not be prepared to answer a question on grants or contracts their organizations receive. By requiring disclosure for all witnesses who receive federal funds, this rule eliminates the perception that a particular witness is under increased scrutiny because of the content of his or her testimony. Because each committee deals with the same set of interest groups and federal administrators repeatedly, committee or subcommittee chairmen naturally would be hesitant to invoke this rule on a case-by-case basis in order to avoid making beneficiaries of the programs they supervise feel uncomfortable.
<p>
<b>
Q: Why can't committees impose this rule on their own? </b>
<p>
A: Committees could impose a Truth in Testimony rule on their own. However, the "iron triangle" phenomenon, the natural sympathy of committees for the interests they oversee, makes committees reluctant to do so on their own. Truth in Testimony is needed to prevent committees from overlooking, or failing to disclose to Congress and the public, the degree to which hearings are dominated by program beneficiaries.
<p>
<b>
Q: What good will this do if both conservative and liberal advocacy groups are affected? </b>
<p>
A: The goal of the rule is not to penalize or intimidate government grantees or contractors, liberals or conservatives. Truth in Testimony simply aims to give Congress more information about the organization that a witness represents, and to alert Members to potentially self-serving testimony.
<p>
<b>
Q: Could witnesses skirt the rule by claiming that they are not testifying on behalf of the organizations for which they work? </b>
<p>
A: Possibly, but if they later claim to have testified on behalf of the organization they work for, in its official publications or elsewhere, they risk having their testimony stricken from the record. Moreover, if a witness is invited to testify on behalf of an organization, he would be expected to provide disclosure for that organization.
<p>
<b>
Q: How would academic experts be affected? </b>
<p>
A: Academic experts (for example, university professors) would be required to disclose any grants they personally received: for instance, research grants from the National Endowment for the Humanities or the National Institutes of Health. Such experts would not have to disclose grants to their university unless they were representing that university in an official capacity, as opposed to presenting their own expert views. In contrast, an assistant dean testifying on federal financial aid programs obviously should disclose his institution's grant receipts. The final authority to decide if a witness has been called as a representative of a particular organization rests with the committee chairmen who administer the rule.
<p>
<b>
Q: Does this disclosure requirement include companies or individuals who receive tax incentives or tax credits? </b>
<p>
A: No. Only direct federal funding -- contracts and grants -- is included in the rule, because this information is readily available for witnesses and can be checked by staff members. Tax incentives normally benefit an entire class of groups or individuals, while a grant is given directly to a particular organization. In addition, organizations testifying regarding tax provisions or exemptions normally are very direct in addressing the status of organizations or individuals they represent.
<p>
<b>
Q: How would this proposal affect defense contractors? </b>
<p>
A: Witnesses from defense contractors would be required to disclose the amount and source of their contracts, in the same manner as contractors for the Department of Energy, or independent agencies such as the Environmental Protection Agency or NASA. Such information is already regularly disclosed by federal defense contractors, often in their annual reports. 
<p>
<b>
Q: Would this include testimony by personnel from federal agencies or the White House?</b>
<p>A: No. In contrast to public witnesses, Congress already knows that witnesses from federal agencies are funded by tax dollars. Further, federal agencies themselves are not normally the beneficiaries of grant programs. 
<p>
<b>
Q: Would Truth in Testimony affect oral testimony? </b>
<p>
A: The Rules of the House currently require witnesses to submit written testimony when practicable. This rule change requires disclosure of federal funding in the written statement, and not in the witness's oral summation.
<p>
<b>
Q: Does it include letters to the committee or the chairman? </b>
<p>
A: This type of unsolicited lobbying would be affected only if a committee decided to print it in the hearing volume. In that event, staff members could contact an organization for information on grants or contracts.
<p>
<b>
Q: Would Truth in Testimony affect lobbying outside of a committee hearing? </b>
<p>
A: No. The rule would apply only to committee hearings and not to informal contacts at committee, Member, or other offices.
<p>
<b>
Q: What is the official form and language of the Truth in Testimony proposal? </b>
<p>

A: As introduced by Representative Doolittle, the proposal reads:

<p>
<blockquote>
	Clause 2(j) of the Rules of the House of Representatives is amended by adding at the end the following new subparagraph:

	"(3)(A) Whenever any hearing is to be conducted by any committee upon any measure or matter, the chairman shall notify all prospective witnesses that written statements submitted to the committee shall include the following information: the amount and source (by agency and program) of any Federal grant (including subgrants from other organizations or from a State pursuant to a Federal block grant) received, and contracts entered into, during the current and previous two fiscal years, by witnesses and any organizations they represent.

	(B) If any witness at a committee hearing fails to make a good faith disclosure of the information required by subdivision (A), then all testimony of that witness at that hearing shall be expunged from the hearing record."
</blockquote>
<p>
<b>Endnotes:</b>
<p><ol>
<li>For further information, see Charles P. Griffin, "Truth in Testimony: Uncovering the Real Special Interests," Heritage Foundation <i>Executive Memorandum</i> No. 422, July 26, 1995.
</ol>
<p>
<center><a href="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></center>
<br>

